SIMPLE: use
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Use
<hw>Use</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>us</ets> use,
usage, L. <ets>usus</ets>, from <ets>uti</ets>, p. p. <ets>usus</ets>,
to use. See <er>Use</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of employing anything, or of applying it to
one's service; the state of being so employed or applied; application;
employment; conversion to some purpose; <as>as, the <ex>use</ex> of a
pen in writing; his machines are in general <ex>use</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Books can never teach the <qex>use</qex> of books.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This Davy serves you for good <qex>uses</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When he framed⟦br⟧
All things to man's delightful <qex>use</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Occasion or need to employ; necessity; <as>as, to
have no further <ex>use</ex> for a book</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Yielding of service; advantage derived; capability
of being used; usefulness; utility.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God made two great lights, great for their <qex>use</qex>⟦br⟧
To man.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>'T is <qex>use</qex> alone that sanctifies expense.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Continued or repeated practice; customary
employment; usage; custom; manner; habit.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let later age that noble <qex>use</qex> envy.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How weary, stale, flat and unprofitable,⟦br⟧
Seem to me all the <qex>uses</qex> of this world!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Common occurrence; ordinary experience.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O Caesar! these things are beyond all <qex>use</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <fld>(Eccl.)</fld> <def>The special form of ritual
adopted for use in any diocese; <as>as, the Sarum, or Canterbury,
<ex>use</ex>; the Hereford <ex>use</ex>; the York <ex>use</ex>; the
Roman <ex>use</ex>; etc</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>From henceforth all the whole realm shall have but one
<qex>use</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Pref. to Book of Common
Prayer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>The premium paid for the possession and employment
of borrowed money; interest; usury.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou art more obliged to pay duty and tribute, <qex>use</qex> and
principal, to him.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>8.</sn> <ety>[In this sense probably a corruption of OF.
<ets>oes</ets>, fr. L. <ets>opus</ets> need, business, employment, work.
Cf. <er>Operate</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The benefit or profit
of lands and tenements. <xex>Use</xex> imports a trust and confidence
reposed in a man for the holding of lands. He to whose <xex>use</xex> or
benefit the trust is intended shall enjoy the profits. An estate is
granted and limited to A for the <xex>use</xex> of B.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>9.</sn> <fld>(Forging)</fld> <def>A stab of iron welded to the
side of a forging, as a shaft, near the end, and afterward drawn down,
by hammering, so as to lengthen the forging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Contingent use</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Springing use</b></col></mcol> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a use to
come into operation on a future uncertain event.</cd> -- <col><b>In
use</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>In employment; in customary practice
observance.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>In heat; -- said especially of
mares.</cd> <au>J. H. Walsh.</au> -- <col><b>Of no use</b></col>,
<cd>useless; of no advantage.</cd> -- <col><b>Of use</b></col>,
<cd>useful; of advantage; profitable.</cd> -- <col><b>Out of
use</b></col>, <cd>not in employment.</cd> -- <col><b>Resulting
use</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>a use, which, being limited by the
deed, expires or can not vest, and results or returns to him who raised
it, after such expiration.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>Secondary
use</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Shifting use</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a
use which, though executed, may change from one to another by
circumstances.</cd> <au>Blackstone.</au> -- <col><b>Statute of
uses</b></col> <fld>(Eng. Law)</fld>, <cd>the stat. 27 Henry VIII., cap.
10, which transfers uses into possession, or which unites the use and
possession.</cd> -- <mcol><col><b>To make use of</b></col>, <col><b>To
put to use</b></col></mcol>, <cd>to employ; to derive service from; to
use.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Use</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Use
<hw>Use</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Used</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Using</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>usen</ets>, F.
<ets>user</ets> to use, use up, wear out, LL. <ets>usare</ets> to use,
from L. <ets>uti</ets>, p. p. <ets>usus</ets>, to use, OL.
<ets>oeti</ets>, <ets>oesus</ets>; of uncertain origin. Cf.
<er>Utility</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make use of; to convert to one's service; to
avail one's self of; to employ; to put a purpose; <as>as, to
<ex>use</ex> a plow; to <ex>use</ex> a chair; to <ex>use</ex> time; to
<ex>use</ex> flour for food; to <ex>use</ex> water for
irrigation.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Launcelot Gobbo, <qex>use</qex> your legs.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some other means I have which may be <qex>used</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To behave toward; to act with regard to; to treat;
<as>as, to <ex>use</ex> a beast cruelly</as>.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧I will
<xex>use</xex> him well.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>How wouldst thou <qex>use</qex> me now?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Cato has <qex>used</qex> me ill.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To practice customarily; to make a practice of;
<as>as, to <ex>use</ex> diligence in business</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Use</qex> hospitality one to another.</q> <rj><qau>1 Pet. iv.
9.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To accustom; to habituate; to render familiar by
practice; to inure; -- employed chiefly in the passive participle;
<as>as, men <ex>used</ex> to cold and hunger; soldiers <ex>used</ex> to
hardships and danger</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I am so <qex>used</qex> in the fire to blow.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou with thy compeers,⟦br⟧
<qex>Used</qex> to the yoke, draw'st his triumphant wheels.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To use one's self</b></col>, <cd>to behave.</cd>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧Pray, forgive me, if I have <xex>used
myself</xex> unmannerly.⟦rdquo⟧ <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>To use
up</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd> <cd>To consume or exhaust by using; to leave
nothing of; <as>as, <ex>to use up</ex> the supplies</as>.</cd>
<sd>(b)</sd> <cd>To exhaust; to tire out; to leave no capacity of force
or use in; to overthrow; <as>as, he was <ex>used up</ex> by
fatigue</as>.</cd> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Employ.</syn> <usage> -- <er>Use</er>,
<er>Employ</er>. We <xex>use</xex> a thing, or <xex>make use</xex> of
it, when we derive from it some enjoyment or service. We
<xex>employ</xex> it when we turn that service into a particular
channel. We <xex>use</xex> words to express our general meaning; we
<xex>employ</xex> certain technical terms in reference to a given
subject. To <xex>make use of</xex>, implies passivity in the thing;
<as>as, to <ex>make use of</ex> a pen</as>; and hence there is often a
material difference between the two words when applied to persons. To
speak of ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>making use</xex> of another⟦rdquo⟧ generally
implies a degrading idea, as if we had <xex>used</xex> him as a tool;
while <xex>employ</xex> has no such sense. A confidential friend is
<xex>employed</xex> to negotiate; an inferior agent is <xex>made use
of</xex> on an intrigue.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I would, my son, that thou wouldst <qex>use</qex> the power⟦br⟧
Which thy discretion gives thee, to control⟦br⟧
And manage all.</q> <rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To study nature will thy time <qex>employ</qex>:⟦br⟧
Knowledge and innocence are perfect joy.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Use</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Use
<hw>Use</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To be wont
or accustomed; to be in the habit or practice; <as>as, he <ex>used</ex>
to ride daily</as>; -- now disused in the present tense, perhaps because
of the similarity in sound, between ⟦ldquo⟧<xex>use</xex> to,⟦rdquo⟧ and
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>used</xex> to.⟦rdquo⟧</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>use</qex> to place him that shall be their captain on a
stone.</q> <rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fears <qex>use</qex> to be represented in an imaginary.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus we <qex>use</qex> to say, it is the room that smokes, when
indeed it is the fire in the room.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now Moses <qex>used</qex> to take the tent and to pitch it without
the camp.</q> <rj><qau>Ex. xxxiii. 7 (Rev. Ver.)</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be accustomed to go; to frequent; to inhabit; to
dwell; -- sometimes followed by <xex>of</xex>.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
⟦ldquo⟧Where never foot did <xex>use</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He <qex>useth</qex> every day to a merchant's house.</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Ye valleys low, where the mild whispers <qex>use</qex>⟦br⟧
Of shades, and wanton winds, and gushing brooks.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Useful</ent>⟦br⟧
